<h2>Purpose</h2>
<p>
  Grounds the <strong>composable / configurable</strong> thesis of the self-driven-project methodology
  (<a href="/backlog/690-is-the-self-driven-project-methodology-a-first-class-constel/">#690</a>,
  <a href="/backlog/672-self-driven-project-tool-agnostic-artefact-contract-everythi/">#672</a>,
  <a href="/backlog/703-survey-agentic-sdlc-approaches-and-expose-every-opinionated-/">#703</a>): survey
  how the field runs agentic / autonomous software delivery, then <strong>extract every opinionated
  practice and classify each</strong> as a configurable <em>dimension</em> carrying a default, a fixed
  <em>invariant</em>, or a recipe-level <em>house-style knob</em> — never a forced mechanic where both
  states are coherent. The motivating example: <a href="https://asdlc.io/practices/micro-commits/">ASDLC.io</a>
  prescribes <strong>micro-commits</strong>. A good practice — but a <em>preference</em>, not something a
  standard should <em>force</em>; so it becomes a knob with a sensible default a project can override.
</p>
<p>
  This is the WE positioning made concrete: every opinionated rival practice shows up as a dial, the
  meta-schemas stay open (the Web Intents lesson — standardize the <em>shape</em>, not the list), and
  nothing coherent is mandated. The survey verifies the <a href="/backlog/665-self-driven-project-ratify-the-framing-autonomy-taxonomy-mas/">#665</a>
  invariant and feeds #672 Layer 1's <strong>autonomy-level registry</strong> and <strong>value/risk-ODD
  dimension registry</strong>, plus the <strong>default recipe</strong> knob values.
</p>

<h2>Method &amp; provenance (no silent over-claiming)</h2>
<p>
  The four named tool/vendor classes (<a href="https://asdlc.io/">ASDLC.io</a> micro-commits + merge-to-main
  governance boundary; <a href="https://tessl.io/blog/tessl-launches-spec-driven-framework-and-registry/">Tessl</a>
  spec-centric framework + Spec Registry; <a href="https://docs.coderabbit.ai/">CodeRabbit</a> AI-review-in-loop
  with YAML custom rules; <a href="https://www.swarmia.com/product/engineering-metrics/">Swarmia</a> DORA/SPACE
  metrics + working agreements) and the lead academic framing
  (<a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/2509.06216">arXiv 2509.06216</a> — Hassan et&nbsp;al., "Agentic Software
  Engineering: Foundational Pillars and a Research Roadmap" / SE&nbsp;3.0) were <strong>web-verified</strong> in
  this pass. The everything-as-code governance prior art (GitOps / OpenGitOps, OSCAL, SPDX), the
  beyond-code framing (<a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/2510.19692">arXiv 2510.19692</a>), the
  software-factory writeups (Forrester / HCLTech / PwC) and the observability/assistant tools (Dash0,
  Augment) are summarized from prior knowledge with spot-verification; treat their specific knob values
  as <em>candidate</em> until a refresh deep-fetches them. None of the classifications below is a blocking
  fork — they are defaults to ratify in #672.
</p>

<h2>The classification rule (per practice)</h2>
<p>Apply the WE fork-existence + dimension-vs-fixed-mechanic tests:</p>
<ol>
  <li><strong>Both states legitimate end-states</strong> &rarr; a <strong>configurable dimension</strong>,
    default = the <em>most permissive / most-flexible</em> value; the restriction is the project's opt-in.</li>
  <li><strong>Exactly one correct branch</strong> (the other is flawed / won't-work) &rarr; <strong>bake it
    as a fixed invariant</strong> (don't expose a fake knob).</li>
  <li><strong>Legit but house style</strong> &rarr; a <strong>recipe-level preference</strong> (a knob with a
    default in the reference recipe), not a meta-schema dimension.</li>
</ol>
<p>
  And the structural finding the survey kept hitting: most field-mandated practices are <em>not</em> new
  dimensions at all — they <strong>map onto one of WE's two existing axes</strong> (per #690's two layers):
  the <strong>autonomy-level ladder</strong> (<a href="/backlog/141-dev-browser-autonomy-toggle-map/">#141</a> /
  #690) or a <strong>value/risk-ODD tolerance</strong>. The survey maps each onto those axes rather than
  inventing a parallel dimension.
</p>

