<h2>Finding — the thesis holds, and the axes are already drawn</h2>
<ul>
  <li><strong>Almost nothing is a fixed invariant.</strong> Only two things resist a knob: the
    everything-as-code <em>foundation</em> (declarative + version-controlled artefacts — the OpenGitOps
    floor) and the <em>gate-checks-outcome-not-authoring-order</em> principle. Everything else a rival
    framework <em>mandates</em> is, in WE's model, a dial.</li>
  <li><strong>Most "practices" collapse onto the two existing axes.</strong> Merge-to-main boundaries,
    mandatory review, consultation packs, PR-vs-direct — all are <strong>autonomy-ladder rungs</strong>
    (#141/#690). Coverage thresholds, quality gates, metrics targets — all are <strong>value/risk-ODD
    tolerances</strong>. The survey did <em>not</em> need to invent parallel dimensions for them; this is
    the strongest confirmation of #690's two-layer framing.</li>
  <li><strong>The genuinely-new dimensions are few and small:</strong> commit-granularity, branching-model,
    test-timing, squash/merge — each with a most-flexible default. House-style items (commit-msg format,
    conventional commits) are recipe knobs, not meta-schema dimensions.</li>
  <li><strong>The artefact-contract prior art is real and convergent:</strong> Tessl's Spec Registry,
    GitOps's declarative store, OSCAL's control-as-code, SPDX's provenance, and SE&nbsp;3.0's MRP/CRP packs
    are all instances of "methodology + evidence as versioned, machine-readable artefacts" — the white
    space WE occupies is the <em>open, no-lock-in, composable</em> contract over them (report §7.4), not a
    new vendor silo.</li>
</ul>

<h2>What this feeds</h2>
<ul>
  <li><strong>#672 Layer 1</strong> — the autonomy-level registry (the rungs surfaced above) and the
    value/risk-ODD dimension registry (the tolerances), each with the default flavor named here, plus the
